1
00:00:01,921 --> 00:00:03,641
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

2
00:00:36,321 --> 00:00:38,881
(# WOKE UP THIS MORNING
WITH MY MIND STAYED ON FREEDOM)

3
00:00:52,521 --> 00:00:54,521
(SINGING STOPS ABRUPTLY)

4
00:01:11,121 --> 00:01:14,801
Hey, you. You don't go that way.

5
00:01:15,721 --> 00:01:17,721
That way is not for coloreds.

6
00:01:19,361 --> 00:01:21,881
Get off, go around the back
and get on there.

7
00:01:21,961 --> 00:01:24,481
That's your entrance. You know that.

8
00:01:25,281 --> 00:01:27,001
I don't see the need...

9
00:01:27,401 --> 00:01:29,321
for getting off, then back on there,

10
00:01:29,401 --> 00:01:32,481
not when there is folks standing
in the stairwell.

11
00:01:33,961 --> 00:01:35,921
How am I gonna squeeze on there?

12
00:01:36,921 --> 00:01:38,801
If you ain't going
through that back door,

13
00:01:39,721 --> 00:01:41,081
you're getting off my bus.

14
00:01:41,161 --> 00:01:42,201
Sir, let me go.

15
00:01:43,361 --> 00:01:45,401
Please don't do that, sir. Stop!

16
00:01:53,601 --> 00:01:56,001
(PEOPLE MURMURING)

17
00:02:03,961 --> 00:02:05,201
You better not hit me.

18
00:02:05,281 --> 00:02:06,921
Get out that door!

19
00:02:25,481 --> 00:02:26,721
Hey!

20
00:02:28,161 --> 00:02:29,161
Hey!

21
00:02:29,401 --> 00:02:32,121
Hey, hold on. Stop!

22
00:02:56,721 --> 00:02:58,921
(WHOOSHING)

23
00:03:09,321 --> 00:03:10,441
Nearly.

24
00:03:13,041 --> 00:03:15,521
-YASMIN: Sheffield?
-Almost. Really close.

25
00:03:16,001 --> 00:03:17,001
So, not Sheffield then.

26
00:03:17,281 --> 00:03:18,921
You're doing this deliberately,
aren't you?

27
00:03:19,001 --> 00:03:20,201
Who are you talking to?

28
00:03:20,281 --> 00:03:21,681
If it's me, I haven't touched anything.

29
00:03:21,761 --> 00:03:23,001
I'm talking to the TARDIS.

30
00:03:23,161 --> 00:03:25,281
'Cause this is our ninth attempt.

31
00:03:25,361 --> 00:03:28,001
Fourteenth.
You can't control this thing, can you?

32
00:03:28,081 --> 00:03:29,921
Excuse me? Yes, I can.

33
00:03:30,121 --> 00:03:31,121
Most of the time.

34
00:03:31,201 --> 00:03:33,521
Just sometimes, like now,
it has a mind of its own.

35
00:03:33,721 --> 00:03:35,561
So, where are we, actually?

36
00:03:35,641 --> 00:03:38,121
Earth. United States.

37
00:03:39,721 --> 00:03:42,201
1955, Montgomery, Alabama,

38
00:03:42,281 --> 00:03:43,521
if I'm reading this properly.

39
00:03:43,601 --> 00:03:45,681
New displays.
Still figuring them out.

40
00:03:45,761 --> 00:03:47,521
19557

41
00:03:47,761 --> 00:03:49,081
Elvis. Could we see Elvis?

42
00:03:49,161 --> 00:03:50,601
I think he's in New York this week.

43
00:03:50,721 --> 00:03:51,801
I could give him a call.

44
00:03:51,881 --> 00:03:53,281
You haven't got Elvis's phone number?

45
00:03:53,361 --> 00:03:55,601
Don't ever tell anyone
I lent him a mobile phone.

46
00:03:55,681 --> 00:03:57,441
(BUZZING)

47
00:03:58,601 --> 00:03:59,801
Whoa.

48
00:04:00,561 --> 00:04:01,561
What's that?

49
00:04:01,641 --> 00:04:03,121
Traces of Artron energy?

50
00:04:03,201 --> 00:04:04,681
Should we know what Artron energy is?

51
00:04:04,761 --> 00:04:06,961
It's the same type of energy
that TARDIS runs off.

52
00:04:07,041 --> 00:04:09,361
There really shouldn't be traces
of Artron energy here.

53
00:04:09,441 --> 00:04:11,001
Unless they are ours, which they're not.

54
00:04:11,081 --> 00:04:12,401
And now you want to check it out?

55
00:04:12,481 --> 00:04:13,481
Yeah, I should.

56
00:04:13,561 --> 00:04:16,001
Quick look, but quietly.
History is very delicate.

57
00:04:16,081 --> 00:04:17,321
We stick together.

58
00:04:22,041 --> 00:04:26,041
Real life 1950s.
Time travel's awesome!

59
00:04:27,201 --> 00:04:28,201
RYAN: Excuse me?

60
00:04:29,561 --> 00:04:30,561
Excuse me?

61
00:04:31,401 --> 00:04:32,401
You dropped this.

62
00:04:37,201 --> 00:04:39,681
Get your filthy black hands off my wife.

63
00:04:39,761 --> 00:04:42,121
-Stop it!
-Please, take a step back.

64
00:04:42,361 --> 00:04:43,521
DOCTOR: Are you okay, Ryan?

65
00:04:43,601 --> 00:04:45,401
I was just trying
to give her back her glove.

66
00:04:45,561 --> 00:04:46,561
Is this your boy?

67
00:04:46,641 --> 00:04:47,841
It's my grandson, actually.

68
00:04:47,921 --> 00:04:49,801
-Your what?
-My grandson.

69
00:04:50,721 --> 00:04:51,961
You ain't from around here.

70
00:04:52,041 --> 00:04:53,121
We don't want any trouble.

71
00:04:53,201 --> 00:04:55,521
I don't know how it goes
where you folks are from,

72
00:04:55,601 --> 00:04:58,721
but your boy, he'll be swinging from
a tree with a noose for a neckerchief

73
00:04:58,801 --> 00:05:00,961
if he touches a white woman
in Montgomery.

74
00:05:01,041 --> 00:05:03,001
-What did you just...
-Is there a problem here, Mr Steele?

75
00:05:03,081 --> 00:05:05,201
Step away now, go ahead.
Step away.

76
00:05:07,681 --> 00:05:09,041
-Friends of yours?
-No, sir.

77
00:05:09,601 --> 00:05:12,241
Just on my lunch break,
wondering if I can help out

78
00:05:12,321 --> 00:05:13,921
with any misunderstanding.

79
00:05:15,321 --> 00:05:17,641
I believe your suit
will be ready tomorrow.

80
00:05:17,921 --> 00:05:20,921
The alterations are going
to make it look just right, sir.

81
00:05:26,521 --> 00:05:27,961
Let's go, Lizzie.

82
00:05:31,001 --> 00:05:32,641
-Are you crazy?
-He slapped me.

83
00:05:32,761 --> 00:05:33,961
Do you read the newspapers?

84
00:05:34,041 --> 00:05:36,001
You know what they did
to young Emmett Till.

85
00:05:36,081 --> 00:05:39,081
-We're from out of town.
-So was Emmett Till.

86
00:05:39,641 --> 00:05:42,681
On vacation from the north,
couple of words to...

87
00:05:43,361 --> 00:05:46,921
a white woman in Mississippi,
and the next thing,

88
00:05:47,161 --> 00:05:50,641
they find his body in the river.

89
00:05:52,081 --> 00:05:53,361
You want that to be you?

90
00:05:53,641 --> 00:05:54,641
No.

91
00:05:55,081 --> 00:05:57,001
Did your mother raise you
with no manners?

92
00:05:57,081 --> 00:05:58,601
I will take a "No, ma'am.”

93
00:05:58,961 --> 00:05:59,961
No, ma'am.

94
00:06:00,641 --> 00:06:03,361
-You all together?
-Yes, we're very grateful, Miss...

95
00:06:03,441 --> 00:06:06,641
Mrs Parks. Rosa Parks.

96
00:06:07,241 --> 00:06:08,241
No way.

97
00:06:08,321 --> 00:06:10,081
-You kidding?
-Brilliant!

98
00:06:10,561 --> 00:06:13,721
Rosa Parks?
Lovely to meet you, Rosa Parks. Big fan.

99
00:06:13,801 --> 00:06:14,881
Excuse me?

100
00:06:14,961 --> 00:06:16,761
Big fan of...

101
00:06:17,241 --> 00:06:18,321
Montgomery.

102
00:06:18,641 --> 00:06:20,641
I am... We are just visiting.

103
00:06:22,321 --> 00:06:25,201
Recommend anything for tourists like us?

104
00:06:25,281 --> 00:06:28,561
I recommend you get yourselves
the hell out of Alabama

105
00:06:28,641 --> 00:06:31,161
before you find yourselves in trouble
you can't get out of.

106
00:06:34,361 --> 00:06:35,481
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

107
00:06:35,561 --> 00:06:36,601
Oh, my God.

108
00:06:36,801 --> 00:06:39,041
Can you believe it? Actual Rosa Parks.

109
00:06:39,121 --> 00:06:40,121
Amazing.

110
00:06:41,481 --> 00:06:42,601
Also a problem.

111
00:06:42,721 --> 00:06:45,241
Registering traces of Artron energy
all around her.

112
00:06:45,321 --> 00:06:46,841
Why is that?

113
00:06:55,281 --> 00:06:56,561
(DEVICE HUMMING)

114
00:06:57,681 --> 00:06:58,681
(BEEPS)

115
00:07:00,481 --> 00:07:01,481
No.

116
00:07:23,361 --> 00:07:24,641
Force shields.

117
00:07:30,281 --> 00:07:32,241
YASMIN:
We were in Rosa Parks class in primary.

118
00:07:32,441 --> 00:07:33,441
Do you remember?

119
00:07:33,681 --> 00:07:36,921
All the Year 4, 5 and 6 classes
were named after inspirational people.

120
00:07:37,001 --> 00:07:38,201
She's the bus woman, right?

121
00:07:38,281 --> 00:07:39,801
-You do remember what she did?
-Yeah.

122
00:07:39,881 --> 00:07:41,481
First black woman to ever drive a bus.

123
00:07:41,561 --> 00:07:43,121
-No, Ryan.
-RYAN: What?

124
00:07:43,201 --> 00:07:45,561
Your nan would have a fit right now.

125
00:07:45,641 --> 00:07:48,201
How could you have been in a class
named after the woman,

126
00:07:48,281 --> 00:07:49,441
and not know who she is?

127
00:07:49,521 --> 00:07:50,521
She's American.

128
00:07:50,601 --> 00:07:53,801
She refused to give up her seat on
a segregated bus to a white passenger.

129
00:07:54,281 --> 00:07:55,801
And got arrested for it.

130
00:07:56,241 --> 00:07:58,801
Her arrest started a boycott
of the buses in Montgomery.

131
00:07:58,881 --> 00:08:00,201
Or rather, will start.

132
00:08:00,521 --> 00:08:03,921
Today is Wednesday, November 30th, 1955.

133
00:08:04,481 --> 00:08:07,561
Tomorrow, Rosa refuses
to give up her seat.

134
00:08:07,641 --> 00:08:10,281
And all this basically kicked off
the US civil rights movement

135
00:08:10,361 --> 00:08:12,121
led by Martin Luther King.

136
00:08:12,201 --> 00:08:13,881
See, I'm not totally ignorant.

137
00:08:14,001 --> 00:08:16,081
I just got confused
by the whole bus thing.

138
00:08:16,161 --> 00:08:19,401
Martin Luther King is a minister here
in Montgomery, right now.

139
00:08:19,481 --> 00:08:21,081
-He and Rosa knew each other?
-Yeah.

140
00:08:22,161 --> 00:08:24,601
Is it me, or has it gone
very quiet in here?

141
00:08:27,761 --> 00:08:30,161
We don't serve Negroes.

142
00:08:36,441 --> 00:08:37,441
Good.

143
00:08:37,721 --> 00:08:39,001
Because I don't eat them.

144
00:08:40,121 --> 00:08:42,121
Or Mexicans.

145
00:08:42,361 --> 00:08:43,361
Is she talking to me?

146
00:08:43,441 --> 00:08:45,641
WAITRESS: You all need to eat
somewhere else.

147
00:08:51,521 --> 00:08:52,521
Come on.

148
00:09:00,601 --> 00:09:02,321
Okay, listen, I can deal with this.

149
00:09:02,401 --> 00:09:04,281
You guys go back to the TARDIS
and be safe.

150
00:09:04,361 --> 00:09:05,721
-While you do what?
-Locate the source

151
00:09:05,801 --> 00:09:07,481
of these energy anomalies.

152
00:09:07,561 --> 00:09:09,761
We're one day out of a tipping point
in earth history,

153
00:09:09,841 --> 00:09:11,721
I don't want anything disrupting that.

154
00:09:12,721 --> 00:09:14,001
It's easy for me here.

155
00:09:14,081 --> 00:09:15,321
It's more dangerous for you.

156
00:09:16,281 --> 00:09:17,601
You can walk away from this.

157
00:09:17,681 --> 00:09:20,361
-Rosa Parks can't.
-Rosa Parks doesn't.

158
00:09:20,441 --> 00:09:23,921
If she can live here all her life,
a couple of hours ain't gonna kill me.

159
00:09:24,681 --> 00:09:26,081
-It ain't gonna kill me, right?
-No.

160
00:09:26,161 --> 00:09:27,761
Not if we look out for each other.

161
00:09:27,841 --> 00:09:30,921
I'm cool with it.
What do you reckon, Mexican lady?

162
00:09:31,001 --> 00:09:32,001
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER HUMMING)

163
00:09:32,081 --> 00:09:34,521
Oi, keep that up,
I'LL use you as a pinata.

164
00:09:34,601 --> 00:09:37,521
Epicentre of the Artron region
is 1.2 miles that way.

165
00:09:37,601 --> 00:09:38,601
-Come on.
-Hey, hey.

166
00:09:38,681 --> 00:09:40,601
We will stop somewhere else to eat,
though, won't we?

167
00:09:40,721 --> 00:09:42,001
No time, Graham.

168
00:09:42,081 --> 00:09:43,881
Have you noticed that happens a lot?

169
00:09:44,641 --> 00:09:46,561
I need regular food, that's all.

170
00:09:46,641 --> 00:09:49,401
RYAN: We just got thrown out of a bar
and that's what you're worried about?

171
00:09:49,481 --> 00:09:50,521
GRAHAM: Not just that.

172
00:09:50,641 --> 00:09:53,361
YASMIN: Not sure your stomach"s
compatible with time travel, Graham.

173
00:10:00,841 --> 00:10:02,561
(CHILDREN CHATTERING)

174
00:10:09,001 --> 00:10:10,281
Can I help you?

175
00:10:15,241 --> 00:10:16,801
There a problem here?

176
00:10:18,601 --> 00:10:20,081
(AMERICAN ACCENT) No problem, ma"am.

177
00:10:20,761 --> 00:10:22,481
No problem at all.

178
00:10:29,121 --> 00:10:31,241
DOCTOR: This is where
the Artron signals converge.

179
00:10:31,361 --> 00:10:34,201
YASMIN: At the bus company.
All roads lead to Rosa Parks.

180
00:10:34,281 --> 00:10:35,281
DOCTOR: Yeah.

181
00:10:35,441 --> 00:10:37,881
Bit of a worry.
Let's have a look around.

182
00:10:38,241 --> 00:10:39,641
GRAHAM: I'm not sure about this.

183
00:10:40,681 --> 00:10:42,401
(HUMMING)

184
00:10:44,441 --> 00:10:45,641
RYAN: There's nothing in here.

185
00:10:45,721 --> 00:10:47,281
YASMIN: Why padlock an empty room?

186
00:10:47,361 --> 00:10:48,361
DOCTOR: Unless it's not empty.

187
00:10:52,681 --> 00:10:54,201
GRAHAM: That wasn't there a second ago.

188
00:10:54,441 --> 00:10:55,441
No kidding.

189
00:10:55,521 --> 00:10:57,401
It was there. We just couldn't see it.

190
00:10:57,481 --> 00:10:58,921
Perception filter.

191
00:10:59,361 --> 00:11:01,721
Why would anybody do that to a suitcase?

192
00:11:04,401 --> 00:11:05,681
Can we open it?

193
00:11:05,761 --> 00:11:07,641
Is the right question.

194
00:11:13,121 --> 00:11:15,201
Is anyone excited?
'Cause I'm really excited.

195
00:11:15,281 --> 00:11:16,721
You won't be if it's a bomb.

196
00:11:17,081 --> 00:11:18,921
Don't kill the vibe, Graham.

197
00:11:20,761 --> 00:11:22,921
RYAN: Whoa. Not very '50s.

198
00:11:23,001 --> 00:11:24,201
DOCTOR: I knew it.

199
00:11:24,921 --> 00:11:26,241
See, now there is a problem.

200
00:11:26,321 --> 00:11:28,481
We are not the only ones in Montgomery
who don't belong here.

201
00:11:28,561 --> 00:11:30,161
Any clues what any of that is?

202
00:11:31,241 --> 00:11:32,361
Information brick.

203
00:11:33,721 --> 00:11:35,601
Multi-intercepting surveillance device.

204
00:11:35,681 --> 00:11:36,801
All a bit knackered though.

205
00:11:36,881 --> 00:11:38,361
Well, why has it been left in here?

206
00:11:38,441 --> 00:11:39,441
(GASPS)

207
00:11:41,081 --> 00:11:43,081
This explains the Artron signals.

208
00:11:43,761 --> 00:11:45,281
This is very bad news.

209
00:11:45,361 --> 00:11:46,961
Secondary charger for a...

210
00:11:47,121 --> 00:11:48,241
(LOUD FIRING)

211
00:11:53,201 --> 00:11:54,201
In here.

212
00:12:11,601 --> 00:12:12,721
(WHISPERING) Stay here.

213
00:12:18,601 --> 00:12:20,921
Oi, Brando. Looking for us?

214
00:12:21,001 --> 00:12:22,361
I'm not armed.

215
00:12:24,321 --> 00:12:26,121
Is that suppose
to make me not shoot you?

216
00:12:26,201 --> 00:12:27,281
Ideally.

217
00:12:28,081 --> 00:12:29,081
So,

218
00:12:29,761 --> 00:12:31,681
temporal displacement weapon.

219
00:12:31,961 --> 00:12:33,281
Horrible things. Can't stand them.

220
00:12:33,361 --> 00:12:34,401
Thank you.

221
00:12:34,481 --> 00:12:35,681
Not a compliment.

222
00:12:36,721 --> 00:12:39,281
Takes a lot of power
to displace things in time.

223
00:12:39,361 --> 00:12:42,681
I think you and I both know
your weapon is pretty much out of juice.

224
00:12:43,721 --> 00:12:45,121
And I've got your spare battery.

225
00:12:45,681 --> 00:12:49,801
You've been leaving traces
of residual Artron energy all over 1955.

226
00:12:49,881 --> 00:12:51,441
What are you, the Artron police?

227
00:12:52,561 --> 00:12:56,441
Maybe you are.
Blue box in the alley, is it a TARDIS?

228
00:12:56,961 --> 00:12:58,641
Might be. What's it to you?

229
00:12:59,001 --> 00:13:00,121
It could be worth a lot.

230
00:13:00,721 --> 00:13:02,001
Nah, not that one.

231
00:13:02,081 --> 00:13:05,321
Second hand, huge mileage.
One careless owner.

232
00:13:05,401 --> 00:13:08,441
Mind you, it's better than
a Vortex Manipulator,

233
00:13:08,521 --> 00:13:10,081
like the one on your wrist.

234
00:13:10,161 --> 00:13:12,161
Cheap and nasty time travel.

235
00:13:14,561 --> 00:13:16,841
So, what do you want with Rosa Parks?

236
00:13:17,921 --> 00:13:18,921
Who?

237
00:13:19,081 --> 00:13:21,081
(SIGHS) Now you're being annoying.

238
00:13:21,161 --> 00:13:22,441
The feeling's mutual.

239
00:13:22,521 --> 00:13:23,521
How long have you been here?

240
00:13:23,601 --> 00:13:24,721
Get out of Montgomery.

241
00:13:25,241 --> 00:13:26,721
You're not the first to say that to us.

242
00:13:27,401 --> 00:13:30,361
If I see any of you again,
I will kill you.

243
00:13:31,561 --> 00:13:32,801
Don't threaten me.

244
00:13:39,841 --> 00:13:41,961
Chop chop, on your way now.

245
00:13:45,321 --> 00:13:46,361
(HUMMING)

246
00:13:46,441 --> 00:13:48,241
(LAUGHS) What are you doing?

247
00:13:48,321 --> 00:13:49,681
Come on, gang.

248
00:13:51,921 --> 00:13:53,281
Are we actually leaving?

249
00:13:53,361 --> 00:13:54,921
Not in a million years.

250
00:14:08,441 --> 00:14:10,441
I'm getting pretty sick
of seeing that sign.

251
00:14:11,361 --> 00:14:12,881
So, how are we gonna do this?

252
00:14:12,961 --> 00:14:13,961
(GROANS)

253
00:14:14,041 --> 00:14:15,681
In you come before anyone sees.

254
00:14:16,041 --> 00:14:17,361
Well, this is fun.

255
00:14:17,481 --> 00:14:21,121
Last time I sneaked into someone's room
by a window was Danny Biswas in Year 10.

256
00:14:21,561 --> 00:14:23,721
You just went right down
in my estimation.

257
00:14:24,481 --> 00:14:25,481
All right!

258
00:14:25,561 --> 00:14:28,041
Danny Biswas? He was punching
well above his weight.

259
00:14:28,841 --> 00:14:31,201
Did you just accidentally
pay me a compliment?

260
00:14:32,921 --> 00:14:33,921
Whatever.

261
00:14:34,521 --> 00:14:36,401
GRAHAM: Why can't we just
stay in the TARDIS?

262
00:14:36,481 --> 00:14:39,321
DOCTOR: Our friend with the temporal
displacement weapon has got eyes on it.

263
00:14:39,401 --> 00:14:41,681
We go in and out of there,
we're gonna run into him again.

264
00:14:41,761 --> 00:14:42,841
And I don't want to, just yet.

265
00:14:42,921 --> 00:14:44,841
-Not until we figure this out.
-This is better?

266
00:14:44,921 --> 00:14:46,801
Smuggling ourselves into crummy motels?

267
00:14:46,881 --> 00:14:48,801
I just need a moment to work this out.

268
00:14:48,881 --> 00:14:50,881
Yeah, like, what do we actually know?

269
00:14:50,961 --> 00:14:54,001
Well, 1955, Montgomery.

270
00:14:54,081 --> 00:14:57,201
One day away from Rosa Parks
refusing to give her seat up on a bus.

271
00:14:57,281 --> 00:14:59,441
Meanwhile, we've got
an out of time impostor,

272
00:14:59,521 --> 00:15:02,201
skulking in the bus works
with a temporal displacement weapon.

273
00:15:02,281 --> 00:15:06,201
I understand "weapon,” but not sure
about "temporal displacement.”

274
00:15:06,281 --> 00:15:08,121
Displaces you through time.

275
00:15:08,201 --> 00:15:10,401
A blast hits you,
you're thrown through time

276
00:15:10,481 --> 00:15:12,041
to wherever the user has set it.

277
00:15:12,121 --> 00:15:13,841
He had it set for the very far future.

278
00:15:13,921 --> 00:15:14,961
That's horrible.

279
00:15:15,041 --> 00:15:17,401
Yes, and it uses Artron molecules.

280
00:15:17,481 --> 00:15:20,401
That, plus his Vortex Manipulator

281
00:15:20,521 --> 00:15:23,641
were presumably what the TARDIS detected
when it brought us here.

282
00:15:23,721 --> 00:15:25,681
So, do we think he is trying
to kill Rosa Parks?

283
00:15:25,761 --> 00:15:26,761
Or use that weapon on her?

284
00:15:26,841 --> 00:15:29,601
He is been here a while.
Set up base at the bus works.

285
00:15:29,681 --> 00:15:31,961
If he wanted to get rid of her,
why has he not done it already?

286
00:15:32,521 --> 00:15:34,641
Besides, the sonic picked up
something else on him,

287
00:15:34,721 --> 00:15:36,241
but I need to go back to make sure.

288
00:15:36,321 --> 00:15:37,321
Right.

289
00:15:37,401 --> 00:15:40,121
What do you remember
about Rosa from school?

290
00:15:40,241 --> 00:15:41,761
Oi, whoa. What are you doing?

291
00:15:41,841 --> 00:15:43,601
That is vandalism.
We'll have to pay for that!

292
00:15:43,681 --> 00:15:45,161
Don't worry. Special pen.

293
00:15:45,401 --> 00:15:47,761
No, pack it in. You ain't Banksy.

294
00:15:48,561 --> 00:15:49,561
Or am I?

295
00:15:50,201 --> 00:15:54,241
Rosa takes the bus
on the first of December, 1955.

296
00:15:54,321 --> 00:15:55,641
What time of day?

297
00:15:55,721 --> 00:15:57,801
Evening. She was coming home from work.

298
00:15:57,881 --> 00:15:59,921
I remember because she said,
people thought she didn't stand

299
00:16:00,001 --> 00:16:01,681
because she was tired from working,
but she wasn't.

300
00:16:01,761 --> 00:16:02,761
Where did she work?

301
00:16:02,841 --> 00:16:05,161
I think it was in a shop,
like a department store.

302
00:16:05,241 --> 00:16:08,321
No, no, wait, earlier she told
that git that slapped Ryan,

303
00:16:08,441 --> 00:16:09,881
"Your suit will be ready tomorrow."

304
00:16:10,041 --> 00:16:12,801
That's it, she did clothes repairs.
She was a seamstress.

305
00:16:12,881 --> 00:16:15,041
I mean, is a seamstress.

306
00:16:15,161 --> 00:16:16,641
Can't get used to being in the past.

307
00:16:16,721 --> 00:16:18,281
(BANGING ON DOOR)

308
00:16:19,761 --> 00:16:21,441
-Bathroom.
-Seriously?

309
00:16:21,521 --> 00:16:22,921
Very seriously.

310
00:16:26,081 --> 00:16:28,121
No, Doc, the wall.

311
00:16:30,441 --> 00:16:31,441
(HUMMING)

312
00:16:31,521 --> 00:16:33,521
Banksy doesn't have one of those.

313
00:16:34,681 --> 00:16:35,801
Or have I?

314
00:16:37,641 --> 00:16:39,761
Oh, Officer. What can I do for you?

315
00:16:40,001 --> 00:16:41,441
Can 1 come in, ma'am?

316
00:16:43,161 --> 00:16:44,921
"Ma'am," I still can't get used to that.

317
00:16:46,041 --> 00:16:47,521
Here we are, darling.

318
00:16:47,641 --> 00:16:49,161
This police officer was
so keen to come in

319
00:16:49,241 --> 00:16:50,721
he didn't feel the need
to introduce himself.

320
00:16:50,801 --> 00:16:52,601
Is there a problem, Officer...

321
00:16:52,681 --> 00:16:55,161
Mason. Montgomery police.

322
00:16:56,921 --> 00:16:59,241
I'd offer you a cup but the refreshment
facilities are very poor.

323
00:16:59,321 --> 00:17:00,561
I'll be leaving a note.

324
00:17:00,641 --> 00:17:01,921
British?

325
00:17:02,081 --> 00:17:03,481
(CHUCKLES) How can you tell?

326
00:17:03,641 --> 00:17:05,641
You've been making folks uneasy.

327
00:17:05,761 --> 00:17:06,921
How have we done that?

328
00:17:07,041 --> 00:17:10,641
You don't happen to know
a couple of mongrels, hmm?

329
00:17:10,921 --> 00:17:13,681
Negro boy. Mexican girl.

330
00:17:13,801 --> 00:17:16,161
I don't recognise anyone
by that description.

331
00:17:18,201 --> 00:17:20,481
They say that Negro
has been going around

332
00:17:20,561 --> 00:17:24,081
picking fights with upstanding citizens.

333
00:17:25,721 --> 00:17:28,081
You appreciate it's a...
It's an offence

334
00:17:28,161 --> 00:17:30,401
to harbour coloreds in a room here.

335
00:17:30,681 --> 00:17:33,081
We're not harbouring anyone who
doesn't have the right to be here.

336
00:17:33,161 --> 00:17:34,161
Mmm-hmm.

337
00:17:37,241 --> 00:17:39,241
MASON: What's your business here
in Montgomery?

338
00:17:39,361 --> 00:17:42,081
We are here to pitch an invention.

339
00:17:42,361 --> 00:17:46,241
Yeah, uh, it's a telephone.

340
00:17:47,721 --> 00:17:53,721
That plays music and it's a camera,
also takes photos.

341
00:17:53,961 --> 00:17:55,641
And it's a calendar.

342
00:17:56,161 --> 00:17:58,001
And it sends letters.

343
00:17:58,121 --> 00:18:00,641
-Sounds ridiculous.
-Yeah...

344
00:18:01,121 --> 00:18:02,801
What's your name, sir?

345
00:18:03,161 --> 00:18:04,561
Steve.

346
00:18:06,441 --> 00:18:08,921
Jobs. Steve Jobs.

347
00:18:09,001 --> 00:18:11,561
You being disrespectful with me,
Mr Jobs?

348
00:18:11,641 --> 00:18:14,721
Steve Jobs would never disrespect
a Montgomery police officer, sir.

349
00:18:32,761 --> 00:18:37,521
You get yourselves gone
as soon as your business is concluded.

350
00:18:37,641 --> 00:18:39,201
Mmm-hmm.

351
00:18:44,721 --> 00:18:46,401
I did not warm to him.

352
00:18:48,681 --> 00:18:50,921
RYAN: I'm sick of this place already.

353
00:18:51,081 --> 00:18:52,561
YASMIN: I know.

354
00:18:53,601 --> 00:18:55,881
To be here just as history
is taking place.

355
00:18:56,001 --> 00:18:57,841
This ain't history here, Yaz.

356
00:18:57,961 --> 00:18:59,361
We're hiding behind bins.

357
00:19:00,081 --> 00:19:01,081
(SIGHS)

358
00:19:01,161 --> 00:19:04,321
I'm having to work so hard to keep
my temper, every second here.

359
00:19:04,841 --> 00:19:07,561
I could have slapped that guy back there
as soon as we arrived.

360
00:19:08,521 --> 00:19:10,841
Thank God, my nan taught me
how to keep my temper.

361
00:19:11,721 --> 00:19:13,801
Never give them the excuse.

362
00:19:13,921 --> 00:19:15,161
Yep.

363
00:19:15,441 --> 00:19:17,601
-My dad tells me the same.
-Yeah, see.

364
00:19:18,281 --> 00:19:22,321
It's not like Rosa Parks wipes out
racism from the world forever.

365
00:19:22,521 --> 00:19:26,521
Otherwise, how come I get stopped way
more by the police than my white mates?

366
00:19:27,361 --> 00:19:29,281
Oi, not this police.

367
00:19:29,361 --> 00:19:30,881
Tell me you don't get hassle.

368
00:19:31,121 --> 00:19:34,161
Of course, I do. Especially on the job.

369
00:19:34,281 --> 00:19:36,441
I get called a Paki
when I'm sorting out a domestic,

370
00:19:36,521 --> 00:19:39,201
or a terrorist on the way home
from the mosque.

371
00:19:39,281 --> 00:19:40,721
Yeah, exactly.

372
00:19:41,481 --> 00:19:43,441
But they don't win, those people.

373
00:19:43,801 --> 00:19:45,321
I can be a police officer now

374
00:19:45,401 --> 00:19:47,641
because people like Rosa Parks
fought those battles for me.

375
00:19:47,801 --> 00:19:49,001
For us.

376
00:19:49,601 --> 00:19:52,601
And in 53 years they'll have
a black president as leader.

377
00:19:53,841 --> 00:19:56,641
Who knows where they'll be
50 years after that?

378
00:19:57,481 --> 00:19:59,561
That's proper change.

379
00:20:00,921 --> 00:20:01,921
(RYAN CHUCKLES)

380
00:20:02,921 --> 00:20:05,961
-What?
-Were you born this positive?

381
00:20:06,801 --> 00:20:08,361
Guess so.

382
00:20:08,441 --> 00:20:10,041
Must be my Mexican blood.

383
00:20:10,241 --> 00:20:11,241
(LAUGHS)

384
00:20:13,521 --> 00:20:15,561
Yaz? Ryan?

385
00:20:17,121 --> 00:20:18,641
(HUMMING)

386
00:20:19,761 --> 00:20:23,161
Where were we? We need
as much intel as we can get.

387
00:20:23,281 --> 00:20:26,121
If we're gonna protect Rosa,
we need to know the facts of her life.

388
00:20:26,201 --> 00:20:29,161
Home address. Daily routine.
Where she works.

389
00:20:29,281 --> 00:20:31,881
The route she takes
and the church she attends.

390
00:20:31,961 --> 00:20:34,401
Also the name of the driver she refused.

391
00:20:34,481 --> 00:20:36,081
I know that. It's James Blake.

392
00:20:36,201 --> 00:20:37,481
How do you know that?

393
00:20:37,561 --> 00:20:41,121
Well, your nan when she found out
I was a bus driver, said to me,

394
00:20:41,241 --> 00:20:43,641
"You better not be like James Blake.

395
00:20:43,721 --> 00:20:45,601
"Blake the snake."
That's what she called him.

396
00:20:45,681 --> 00:20:47,641
And I had to ask her who he was,

397
00:20:47,721 --> 00:20:49,521
and she just said he gave
all bus drivers a bad name.

398
00:20:49,601 --> 00:20:51,281
She said that when you'd only just met?

399
00:20:51,361 --> 00:20:52,961
-Yeah.
-That's pretty hard line.

400
00:20:53,041 --> 00:20:54,441
That's my nan.

401
00:20:54,561 --> 00:20:57,641
Yeah. She had a t-shirt that said,

402
00:20:58,641 --> 00:21:00,121
"Spirit of Rosa."

403
00:21:02,681 --> 00:21:04,921
And well, I wish that she was here.

404
00:21:09,921 --> 00:21:11,841
I don't. She'd start a riot.

405
00:21:11,921 --> 00:21:13,801
(ALL LAUGHING)

406
00:21:13,881 --> 00:21:15,561
Right. Operation Rosa Parks.

407
00:21:34,241 --> 00:21:35,841
YASMIN: I found out where she works.

408
00:21:36,001 --> 00:21:37,961
Montgomery Fair Department store.

409
00:21:38,081 --> 00:21:41,441
And if the phone book's right,
this is where she lives.

410
00:21:41,561 --> 00:21:46,601
Right. So, these bus routes don't go
near Rosa's shop or house,

411
00:21:46,681 --> 00:21:49,361
but these ones do.

412
00:21:49,481 --> 00:21:52,841
Great. If we can find Rosa's route
and time today,

413
00:21:52,921 --> 00:21:54,321
we can keep an eye on her tomorrow.

414
00:21:54,441 --> 00:21:56,321
Who's up for a bus ride?

415
00:21:59,761 --> 00:22:01,441
GRAHAM. Sir, excuse me.

416
00:22:01,521 --> 00:22:02,761
Sorry.

417
00:22:02,841 --> 00:22:04,681
Hey, Doc.

418
00:22:06,121 --> 00:22:10,281
This route is one of three that goes
between Rosa's home and where she works.

419
00:22:10,361 --> 00:22:12,001
I reckon this one's the most direct.

420
00:22:12,081 --> 00:22:14,281
DOCTOR: So it's most likely she takes
this one tomorrow night.

421
00:22:14,361 --> 00:22:16,081
But we can't be certain
exactly what time.

422
00:22:16,161 --> 00:22:18,081
Unless we stalk her all day.

423
00:22:21,281 --> 00:22:23,641
This is me. On the back of the bus.

424
00:22:24,521 --> 00:22:27,121
I'm so ashamed.
You shouldn't have to do this.

425
00:22:27,201 --> 00:22:28,921
I agree. I'm sorry, Ryan.

426
00:22:30,441 --> 00:22:32,401
The driver let me on
at the front of the bus.

427
00:22:32,481 --> 00:22:34,841
What does that mean for where I sit?

428
00:22:35,881 --> 00:22:38,921
Obviously not a lot of
Pakistani heritage around here.

429
00:22:39,721 --> 00:22:42,601
Does coloured just mean black in 19557

430
00:22:43,161 --> 00:22:44,161
(SIGHS)

431
00:22:44,241 --> 00:22:46,481
I guess I'll park
my South Asian Mexican backside

432
00:22:46,561 --> 00:22:48,761
in the white section
and let's see what happens.

433
00:22:50,441 --> 00:22:54,161
Riding the bus in Montgomery.
Good times.

434
00:22:55,921 --> 00:22:56,921
(BELL DINGS)

435
00:23:04,041 --> 00:23:05,881
That's where she works.

436
00:23:05,961 --> 00:23:07,601
This must be her stop.

437
00:23:07,681 --> 00:23:10,001
DOCTOR: Perfect. We can wait here,

438
00:23:10,081 --> 00:23:12,201
then get on the bus with her
when she finishes work.

439
00:23:12,281 --> 00:23:13,521
Have a little chat.

440
00:23:18,801 --> 00:23:21,361
Hi. Nice to see you again.

441
00:23:21,481 --> 00:23:22,881
Mrs Parks, right?

442
00:23:22,961 --> 00:23:24,041
Yes.

443
00:23:24,121 --> 00:23:27,001
You helped us out earlier today
with our little misunderstanding.

444
00:23:27,121 --> 00:23:29,681
I remember. British.

445
00:23:29,761 --> 00:23:32,161
Yes, funny thing.
You'll never believe this.

446
00:23:32,361 --> 00:23:35,201
We're actually doing
market research for bus companies.

447
00:23:35,281 --> 00:23:37,081
Looking at people's transport habits.

448
00:23:37,241 --> 00:23:40,401
Answer the questions,
enter the raffle for a prize.

449
00:23:40,561 --> 00:23:42,881
You get this bus this time every day?

450
00:23:43,041 --> 00:23:45,641
Most days. Always this time.

451
00:23:45,761 --> 00:23:47,121
And you live?

452
00:23:47,201 --> 00:23:49,361
Cleveland Court. Next stop.

453
00:23:51,361 --> 00:23:56,641
Ma'am, if you keep sitting there
we're all going to have to move.

454
00:23:57,641 --> 00:23:59,121
What do you mean?

455
00:24:00,041 --> 00:24:03,161
Well, if white folks need seats,

456
00:24:03,521 --> 00:24:06,241
by law, I have to give mine up.

457
00:24:06,321 --> 00:24:09,601
This middle section's only for coloreds
if white folk don't need it.

458
00:24:09,721 --> 00:24:11,201
Well, that's not right.

459
00:24:12,001 --> 00:24:14,241
Tell that to your company, sir.

460
00:24:15,161 --> 00:24:17,201
If I win your raffle, will that give me

461
00:24:17,281 --> 00:24:21,281
the right to sit anywhere
I want on this bus?

462
00:24:22,081 --> 00:24:23,521
No.

463
00:24:25,121 --> 00:24:27,361
I didn't think so.

464
00:24:27,441 --> 00:24:29,521
This is my stop.

465
00:24:32,201 --> 00:24:34,321
I'm gonna follow her.

466
00:24:34,441 --> 00:24:35,761
See what I can find out.

467
00:24:35,881 --> 00:24:37,721
Meet you back at the motel later.

468
00:24:38,441 --> 00:24:40,041
DOCTOR: Ryan.

469
00:24:40,121 --> 00:24:41,761
Be careful.

470
00:24:41,881 --> 00:24:43,321
Yeah.

471
00:24:44,761 --> 00:24:46,281
Do you think he'll be all right?

472
00:24:46,361 --> 00:24:47,561
I hope so.

473
00:24:47,681 --> 00:24:50,561
Graham, do you think you can find
James Blake, the driver?

474
00:24:51,521 --> 00:24:53,801
Um, yeah, I'll just have a talk
with the bloke at the front

475
00:24:53,881 --> 00:24:55,761
and find out where
they all drink.

476
00:24:55,841 --> 00:24:58,561
Yaz, can you compile a timeline
of what happens,

477
00:24:58,641 --> 00:25:00,121
this time tomorrow evening?

478
00:25:00,201 --> 00:25:01,921
Okay. But what are you gonna do?

479
00:25:02,001 --> 00:25:05,001
Talk to our friend.
Tell him to stay out of history's way.

480
00:25:17,961 --> 00:25:21,601
Stalking Rosa Parks!
Don't know about this.

481
00:25:24,681 --> 00:25:26,681
You better not be following me.

482
00:25:28,281 --> 00:25:30,281
-I wanna help.
-With what?

483
00:25:32,561 --> 00:25:33,961
The fight.

484
00:25:35,441 --> 00:25:40,681
And how do I know you're not a spy
for the police or the FBI?

485
00:25:41,241 --> 00:25:42,721
Because if they were gonna send a spy

486
00:25:42,801 --> 00:25:45,561
they would send one who could actually
follow you without being spotted.

487
00:25:45,641 --> 00:25:47,321
And that didn't have a British accent.

488
00:25:47,921 --> 00:25:50,641
Also, don't think they know
any black guys.

489
00:25:51,281 --> 00:25:52,281
(LAUGHS)

490
00:25:56,441 --> 00:25:58,241
You any good at serving coffee?

491
00:26:06,121 --> 00:26:08,241
(DOGS BARKING)

492
00:26:25,961 --> 00:26:27,481
(HUMMING)

493
00:26:33,041 --> 00:26:34,241
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

494
00:26:36,841 --> 00:26:37,841
(GRUNTS)

495
00:26:39,521 --> 00:26:41,481
Oops. Shame.

496
00:26:41,601 --> 00:26:43,841
You just sent all your equipment
to goodness knows where.

497
00:26:43,921 --> 00:26:47,641
79th century
judging by the weapon setting

498
00:26:47,721 --> 00:26:50,241
which, by the way, overheat very easily.

499
00:26:50,321 --> 00:26:51,481
(GRUNTS)

500
00:26:51,561 --> 00:26:53,601
Cheap and nasty. Now we're even.

501
00:26:55,641 --> 00:26:57,441
First things first.

502
00:26:59,121 --> 00:27:00,841
Tell me about Stormcage.

503
00:27:01,561 --> 00:27:04,521
-Storm what?
-Ah, rubbish liar.

504
00:27:04,601 --> 00:27:07,761
On your wrist is a Stormcage identifier.

505
00:27:07,881 --> 00:27:10,801
The most secure prison facility
this side of the universe.

506
00:27:10,881 --> 00:27:12,281
Not in this time zone, of course.

507
00:27:12,361 --> 00:27:15,041
But I guess that's where
the Vortex Manipulator comes in.

508
00:27:15,121 --> 00:27:16,601
It's amazing what you can get

509
00:27:16,681 --> 00:27:19,081
if you're prepared to work
and barter inside that prison.

510
00:27:19,161 --> 00:27:20,641
Escape or release?

511
00:27:20,721 --> 00:27:24,721
I did my time. I'm rehabilitated.

512
00:27:24,801 --> 00:27:26,881
What were you there for
in the first place?

513
00:27:26,961 --> 00:27:30,401
Oh, if I tell you,
it might colour your view of me.

514
00:27:31,081 --> 00:27:33,801
I was young. Nobody got hurt.

515
00:27:34,601 --> 00:27:39,841
Well, a few people got killed.
A few hundred people. Thousand tops.

516
00:27:41,361 --> 00:27:43,041
Two thousand.

517
00:27:45,841 --> 00:27:49,201
And it was nasty enough that Stormcage
placed a neural restrict or in your brain

518
00:27:49,281 --> 00:27:51,241
before releasing you
back into the universe.

519
00:27:52,441 --> 00:27:54,201
How can you know that?

520
00:27:56,161 --> 00:27:58,841
-Who are you?
-Very good scanner, this.

521
00:27:58,921 --> 00:28:00,841
I though I detected it
the first time we met.

522
00:28:00,921 --> 00:28:03,521
And then it started to make sense
because we were wondering...

523
00:28:03,601 --> 00:28:06,641
You've obviously got a problem
with Rosa, why don't you just kill her?

524
00:28:06,721 --> 00:28:09,001
But the answer is, because you can't.

525
00:28:09,521 --> 00:28:14,001
Neural restrict or means you can't kill
or injure any living thing.

526
00:28:14,081 --> 00:28:17,001
It stops you from doing it,
no matter how much you wanna try.

527
00:28:17,521 --> 00:28:21,761
So even if I do this,
smash your Vortex Manipulator...

528
00:28:23,121 --> 00:28:24,121
(GASPING)

529
00:28:24,681 --> 00:28:27,401
Yeah, there it is. Kicking in.

530
00:28:27,481 --> 00:28:29,401
Tied to your brain chemistry.

531
00:28:32,401 --> 00:28:36,281
You can't harm me.
As much as you want to.

532
00:28:36,361 --> 00:28:37,361
Better be nice to me

533
00:28:37,441 --> 00:28:39,641
because I'm your best shot
of getting out of this time zone now.

534
00:28:39,721 --> 00:28:41,081
(GRUNTS)

535
00:28:41,161 --> 00:28:43,841
Neutered criminal on release.

536
00:28:44,721 --> 00:28:46,201
And you come here.

537
00:28:47,721 --> 00:28:50,641
-Why?
-I'm allowed a hobby.

538
00:28:51,361 --> 00:28:53,081
And yours is Rosa Parks?

539
00:28:53,161 --> 00:28:55,081
This is where things
started to go wrong.

540
00:28:56,201 --> 00:28:57,961
And you think you can put them right?

541
00:29:00,121 --> 00:29:02,681
I had a lot of time to think
in Stormcage,

542
00:29:02,761 --> 00:29:06,321
and I realised
tiny actions change the world.

543
00:29:07,841 --> 00:29:09,241
What's your name?

544
00:29:09,321 --> 00:29:12,241
-Krasko.
-Don't like it.

545
00:29:12,361 --> 00:29:15,001
Listen, Krasko,
I will give you one warning.

546
00:29:15,081 --> 00:29:17,721
Go somewhere else.
Find a beach, read a book.

547
00:29:17,801 --> 00:29:20,201
Because you're a criminal
who's lost his kit.

548
00:29:20,281 --> 00:29:21,641
Lost his weapons.

549
00:29:23,121 --> 00:29:24,401
You think that makes a difference?

550
00:29:25,281 --> 00:29:29,281
History changes
when tiny things don't go to plan.

551
00:29:29,361 --> 00:29:31,281
You mean tomorrow.

552
00:29:31,361 --> 00:29:33,281
Won't work.

553
00:29:33,361 --> 00:29:35,321
Not while I'm here.

554
00:29:37,881 --> 00:29:39,281
Well, let's see.

555
00:29:49,041 --> 00:29:52,961
This is Ryan Sinclair.
He's from England.

556
00:29:54,201 --> 00:29:58,961
I'm thinking he might be
a new recruit to our youth council.

557
00:30:00,441 --> 00:30:03,081
I said he could listen in
and serve coffee.

558
00:30:04,321 --> 00:30:07,241
Ah, this is my husband, Parks.

559
00:30:09,281 --> 00:30:11,321
This is Mr Fred Gray.

560
00:30:12,201 --> 00:30:16,921
And this is Dr King
from Dexter Avenue Baptist Church.

561
00:30:17,641 --> 00:30:18,721
What?

562
00:30:18,801 --> 00:30:21,481
-Martin Luther King?
-That's correct.

563
00:30:22,561 --> 00:30:25,081
Oh, my days.
My nan loves you.

564
00:30:26,161 --> 00:30:27,721
Your "nan"?

565
00:30:28,281 --> 00:30:30,401
My gran. Grandma.

566
00:30:30,481 --> 00:30:33,241
The elder ladies do love
your sermons, Martin.

567
00:30:33,921 --> 00:30:37,241
You'll never be short for
a grey-haired wife in Alabama.

568
00:30:37,321 --> 00:30:39,001
She attend Dexter Avenue?

569
00:30:40,001 --> 00:30:42,281
No, she died recently.

570
00:30:43,721 --> 00:30:46,081
I'm sorry for your loss, son.

571
00:30:46,201 --> 00:30:47,801
Thank you.

572
00:30:47,881 --> 00:30:49,681
Thank you, Martin Luther King.

573
00:30:50,561 --> 00:30:52,481
She'd be chuffed to know
that you said that.

574
00:30:52,561 --> 00:30:54,921
-Ryan.
-Excuse me, Dr King.

575
00:30:55,081 --> 00:30:57,001
Yes, Rosa Parks? Whoa.

576
00:30:58,601 --> 00:31:00,481
You want to serve that coffee now?

577
00:31:00,841 --> 00:31:01,881
Yeah.

578
00:31:14,601 --> 00:31:17,321
BLAKE: So you say you're a bus driver
too back in England?

579
00:31:17,441 --> 00:31:20,161
It's a privilege, innit, eh?
Getting people where they want to go.

580
00:31:20,241 --> 00:31:21,441
Being part of the community.

581
00:31:22,281 --> 00:31:25,601
I'm figurin' you ain't got to deal with
keeping coloreds apart from whites.

582
00:31:27,721 --> 00:31:30,921
No. No, we don't do that.

583
00:31:32,081 --> 00:31:33,321
You approve of that, Jim?

584
00:31:33,401 --> 00:31:35,961
Just the way it is.
No matter how much they complain.

585
00:31:36,041 --> 00:31:37,481
Ain't going to change.

586
00:31:39,961 --> 00:31:41,881
Back at it tomorrow, I suppose.

587
00:31:41,961 --> 00:31:44,761
No, going fishing at Mill Creek.

588
00:31:46,921 --> 00:31:50,401
You can't be. It's December the first.

589
00:31:50,481 --> 00:31:51,601
What?

590
00:31:51,681 --> 00:31:54,761
Well, 'cause it's a Thursday, innit?
You know, like a work day.

591
00:31:54,841 --> 00:31:55,841
My rota got changed.

592
00:31:55,921 --> 00:31:58,681
Fella from the depot just came by,
gave me the good news.

593
00:32:05,281 --> 00:32:07,401
Get what you wanted from tonight?

594
00:32:11,241 --> 00:32:13,001
I didn't know what I wanted.

595
00:32:14,441 --> 00:32:16,281
But, yeah.

596
00:32:16,361 --> 00:32:20,281
Meeting you guys. Listening to you
all talk. I can't believe it.

597
00:32:22,281 --> 00:32:23,961
It'll get better, you know.

598
00:32:24,641 --> 00:32:26,041
Not perfect but...

599
00:32:27,961 --> 00:32:29,641
Better.

600
00:32:31,521 --> 00:32:33,001
I hope so.

601
00:32:34,521 --> 00:32:35,841
It's worth the fight.

602
00:32:38,641 --> 00:32:40,081
Thank you.

603
00:32:41,201 --> 00:32:42,801
From me and my nan.

604
00:32:44,481 --> 00:32:46,481
I haven't done anything.

605
00:32:52,361 --> 00:32:54,001
Good night, ma'am.

606
00:32:56,961 --> 00:32:59,041
DOCTOR: Managed to get Krasko's
weapon off him, at least.

607
00:32:59,121 --> 00:33:00,921
(DOOR CLOSES)

608
00:33:01,001 --> 00:33:03,641
James Blake is taking the day off.

609
00:33:03,721 --> 00:33:05,881
-What?
-But he can't.

610
00:33:05,961 --> 00:33:09,161
That's what I said.
Strangely, he didn't listen.

611
00:33:09,281 --> 00:33:11,561
Your mate is interfering.

612
00:33:11,641 --> 00:33:13,521
He has reassigned Blake's route

613
00:33:13,601 --> 00:33:16,681
to a driver called Elias Griffin Junior.

614
00:33:16,801 --> 00:33:20,001
Tiny actions.
That's what Krasko is doing.

615
00:33:20,081 --> 00:33:22,921
See, he's clever. I'll give him that.
He knows.

616
00:33:23,001 --> 00:33:27,081
He is not planning on killing
or destroying or breaking history.

617
00:33:27,161 --> 00:33:31,801
He's planning to nudge it
just enough so that it doesn't happen.

618
00:33:31,881 --> 00:33:34,721
Enough of a stick in the spokes
to throw everything off the rails

619
00:33:34,801 --> 00:33:36,441
and now I'm really mixing
my transport metaphors.

620
00:33:36,521 --> 00:33:39,081
Well, he didn't reckon
with us keeping it in place.

621
00:33:39,161 --> 00:33:41,601
YASMIN: And how do we do that then?

622
00:33:43,321 --> 00:33:46,281
Now we know what our task is.

623
00:33:46,361 --> 00:33:48,921
Keep history in order.

624
00:33:49,921 --> 00:33:50,961
No changing it.

625
00:33:51,041 --> 00:33:55,121
Just guarding it against someone
who wants to disrupt it.

626
00:33:55,201 --> 00:33:58,921
Tomorrow we have to make sure
Rosa Parks gets on the bus

627
00:33:59,001 --> 00:34:02,641
driven by James Blake
and that the bus is full,

628
00:34:02,721 --> 00:34:05,441
so Rosa sits when she is asked
to stand for white passengers.

629
00:34:05,521 --> 00:34:06,841
-(BEEP)
-Ryan, don't mess with that.

630
00:34:06,921 --> 00:34:08,321
How does it even work?

631
00:34:08,401 --> 00:34:11,921
Charger's here, this setting dials
the temporal destination.

632
00:34:12,001 --> 00:34:13,481
Pretty simple, pretty deadly.

633
00:34:13,561 --> 00:34:14,881
Now, can we concentrate?

634
00:34:14,961 --> 00:34:17,241
How are we supposed
to keep history in order

635
00:34:17,321 --> 00:34:19,601
if James Blake is going
to go fishing at Mill Creek

636
00:34:19,681 --> 00:34:21,801
and another driver is lined up
to do his route?

637
00:34:21,881 --> 00:34:23,601
-I've got an idea.
-I've got an idea.

638
00:34:23,681 --> 00:34:24,841
Same idea?

639
00:34:24,921 --> 00:34:26,321
-Raffle winner.
-Fishing takedown.

640
00:34:30,241 --> 00:34:31,801
Elias Griffin Junior?

641
00:34:31,881 --> 00:34:33,801
-Yeah.
-Congratulations.

642
00:34:33,881 --> 00:34:37,921
You are the lucky winner
of our Raffle of the Century.

643
00:34:38,001 --> 00:34:40,081
I don't remembering entering no raffle.

644
00:34:40,201 --> 00:34:43,121
You have won an all expenses paid trip
to Las Vegas.

645
00:34:43,201 --> 00:34:47,761
Front row tickets to see Frank Sinatra
and a VIP pass to meet Frank himself.

646
00:34:47,841 --> 00:34:49,601
My wife loves Sinatra.

647
00:34:49,681 --> 00:34:51,481
Amazing, who would have guessed?

648
00:34:51,561 --> 00:34:54,401
Only one condition,
you have to leave now.

649
00:34:54,481 --> 00:34:55,601
Right now.

650
00:34:55,681 --> 00:34:59,401
Oh, I can't. My work shift starts
in a couple of hours.

651
00:34:59,481 --> 00:35:00,521
We've sorted that too.

652
00:35:00,601 --> 00:35:02,441
Your company has already assigned
someone to cover you.

653
00:35:02,521 --> 00:35:05,121
There's a taxi coming to pick you up
in 30 minutes

654
00:35:05,201 --> 00:35:06,401
to take you to the airport.

655
00:35:06,481 --> 00:35:08,721
-Thirty minutes?
-Unless you don't wanna go.

656
00:35:08,801 --> 00:35:12,561
Oh, we'll be ready. We'll be ready.

657
00:35:12,641 --> 00:35:14,561
(DOCTOR SIGHS)

658
00:35:14,641 --> 00:35:19,041
Good job Elvis lent Frank that mobile
phone against everything I told him.

659
00:35:19,761 --> 00:35:21,401
We need to stick tight to Rosa.

660
00:35:29,761 --> 00:35:31,681
Oi, oi, Jim boy.

661
00:35:31,761 --> 00:35:33,081
How you doing, cockle?

662
00:35:33,161 --> 00:35:34,881
We've been looking for you
all along the creek.

663
00:35:34,961 --> 00:35:36,041
Why?

664
00:35:36,121 --> 00:35:37,561
Well, we thought we'd come and join you.

665
00:35:37,641 --> 00:35:40,081
You saying last night how beautiful
and peaceful it was. Yeah.

666
00:35:40,161 --> 00:35:42,441
This is my grandson, Ryan.

667
00:35:42,521 --> 00:35:43,801
What in the hell?

668
00:35:43,881 --> 00:35:46,321
Yo! Jimmy Blake. What's up, blud?

669
00:35:47,681 --> 00:35:49,041
You can't be here!

670
00:35:49,121 --> 00:35:51,561
Hey, how many have you caught?
Can I pick them up?

671
00:35:51,641 --> 00:35:52,721
Ever seen a man juggle fish?

672
00:35:52,801 --> 00:35:55,201
(SHOUTING) Stay out of my things.
You don't belong here.

673
00:35:55,281 --> 00:35:57,081
And he ain't your grandson.

674
00:35:57,161 --> 00:35:58,881
I reckon we'll be here all day.

675
00:35:58,961 --> 00:36:00,241
Yeah, might as well.

676
00:36:00,321 --> 00:36:03,041
Seeing as that bus sit-in
is kicking off.

677
00:36:03,121 --> 00:36:04,881
-Mmm.
-Gonna be big trouble.

678
00:36:04,961 --> 00:36:06,081
What you say, boy?

679
00:36:06,161 --> 00:36:10,161
Oh, we heard that
a group of black passengers

680
00:36:10,241 --> 00:36:12,481
were planning a sit-in across
all the bus routes tonight.

681
00:36:12,601 --> 00:36:14,201
(CLICKING TONGUE)

682
00:36:14,281 --> 00:36:15,521
Not on my bus, they're not.

683
00:36:15,601 --> 00:36:17,521
You gonna get out of my seat?

684
00:36:17,601 --> 00:36:18,921
Out of my seat!

685
00:36:19,001 --> 00:36:20,241
GRAHAM: All right. Settle down.

686
00:36:23,081 --> 00:36:24,801
Have the damn creek.

687
00:36:26,921 --> 00:36:28,321
(BOTH CHUCKLE)

688
00:36:28,401 --> 00:36:30,001
-He was easy.
-Boom.

689
00:36:31,241 --> 00:36:32,401
Don't do that.

690
00:36:35,241 --> 00:36:37,921
DOCTOR: Mrs Parks,
enormous clothing emergency.

691
00:36:38,001 --> 00:36:39,001
Can you help me?

692
00:36:39,081 --> 00:36:41,641
That is one nasty tear.

693
00:36:41,721 --> 00:36:42,961
Yes, it is.

694
00:36:43,441 --> 00:36:46,241
And there is nothing us Brits hate
more than a clothing emergency.

695
00:36:46,321 --> 00:36:48,881
Mrs Parks, I have to go out
in that coat this evening,

696
00:36:48,961 --> 00:36:50,681
and if it's torn
I'll get in such trouble.

697
00:36:50,761 --> 00:36:52,241
Can you take a look at it now?

698
00:36:52,641 --> 00:36:54,281
Double time Christmas bonus.

699
00:36:58,161 --> 00:37:02,881
Well, I don't have any collections
until tomorrow afternoon.

700
00:37:03,561 --> 00:37:06,641
I guess I could fit you in.

701
00:37:06,721 --> 00:37:09,241
Now, if you come back
just before we close...

702
00:37:09,321 --> 00:37:12,321
I'll wait...while you work.
Keep you company.

703
00:37:13,441 --> 00:37:16,241
-I don't need company.
-No, but my coat does.

704
00:37:16,761 --> 00:37:17,961
It's very valuable.

705
00:37:18,041 --> 00:37:20,041
I don't usually allow it
out of my sight.

706
00:37:20,121 --> 00:37:22,881
Thank you.
You're gonna make a big difference.

707
00:37:23,561 --> 00:37:26,121
Well, I best set to work then.

708
00:37:26,761 --> 00:37:29,161
Don't let her out of your sight.
I'm gonna go meet Graham and Ryan.

709
00:37:29,241 --> 00:37:33,241
Remember, get Rosa out of here
by 5:40, at the latest,

710
00:37:33,321 --> 00:37:34,961
to be on that bus on time.

711
00:37:38,361 --> 00:37:41,161
(TICKING)

712
00:37:42,241 --> 00:37:44,121
BLAKE: I came back
from the creek for this?

713
00:37:44,201 --> 00:37:46,281
Four flat tyres
and a smashed in windshield.

714
00:37:46,361 --> 00:37:47,841
What the hell happened?

715
00:37:48,401 --> 00:37:51,161
-Kids.
-Well, I can't drive that.

716
00:37:51,241 --> 00:37:54,161
Oh, no, you go on home.
We'll cancel the route.

717
00:37:57,481 --> 00:38:01,321
BLAKE: So much for that protest.
This bus ain't going nowhere.

718
00:38:05,001 --> 00:38:06,041
GRAHAM: Did you hear that?

719
00:38:06,121 --> 00:38:07,841
Everything we do,
Krasko's a step ahead.

720
00:38:07,921 --> 00:38:10,241
He must have deliberately smashed up
that bus himself.

721
00:38:10,321 --> 00:38:11,441
RYAN: We've got to fix this.

722
00:38:11,521 --> 00:38:13,801
James Blake has got to drive
Rosa's bus home tonight.

723
00:38:13,881 --> 00:38:15,681
(PANTING)

724
00:38:15,801 --> 00:38:17,681
Right, well,
he ain't giving up that easily.

725
00:38:17,761 --> 00:38:19,081
Well, neither are we.

726
00:38:19,161 --> 00:38:21,921
Ryan, check every bus stop
along Blake's route.

727
00:38:22,001 --> 00:38:25,081
Tell the waiting passengers that the
bus is coming, and they have to wait.

728
00:38:25,161 --> 00:38:26,201
Okay.

729
00:38:26,321 --> 00:38:29,201
Do not let any of the passengers walk.
The bus has to be full.

730
00:38:29,281 --> 00:38:32,281
It has to be crowded enough
so that Rosa is expected to move.

731
00:38:32,361 --> 00:38:34,281
Right, got it. Good luck.

732
00:38:35,201 --> 00:38:37,441
-Now, Graham.
-Mmm-hmm?

733
00:38:37,921 --> 00:38:39,521
Are you thinking what I'm thinking?

734
00:38:40,641 --> 00:38:43,921
GRAHAM: Nicking and hot-wiring a bus
from right outside the depot?

735
00:38:44,001 --> 00:38:46,521
Hope our friendly cop
don't hear about this.

736
00:38:46,601 --> 00:38:47,881
What in the hell?

737
00:38:50,361 --> 00:38:51,841
This is your replacement bus service.

738
00:38:51,921 --> 00:38:53,961
-Jim boy.
-You again.

739
00:38:54,041 --> 00:38:56,761
I know, I literally get everywhere.
Now, come on. Hop in and do your job.

740
00:38:56,841 --> 00:38:58,521
You're already 18 minutes
behind schedule.

741
00:38:58,641 --> 00:39:01,561
How do you know that? What's going on?
What happened to that damn sit-in?

742
00:39:01,641 --> 00:39:03,081
Nobody else knew anything about it.

743
00:39:03,161 --> 00:39:06,161
Love to explain all that to you
but you know us Brits. Very imperious.

744
00:39:06,241 --> 00:39:08,001
Not prone on explaining ourselves
to anyone.

745
00:39:08,081 --> 00:39:09,761
So no time to chat. Just get driving.

746
00:39:09,841 --> 00:39:11,601
Lot of people need
to get on this bus tonight.

747
00:39:12,761 --> 00:39:15,881
(SIGHS) Driver James Blake
behind the wheel, check.

748
00:39:40,881 --> 00:39:43,521
"Bus services suspended.”
No, no, no. Krasko.

749
00:39:44,481 --> 00:39:46,401
Have you always
wanted to be a seamstress?

750
00:39:46,481 --> 00:39:49,281
No, I dreamed of being a teacher.

751
00:39:49,361 --> 00:39:53,241
But my grandmother got sick,
then my mother,

752
00:39:53,361 --> 00:39:56,241
-so that was the end of school.
-Sorry about that.

753
00:39:56,321 --> 00:39:59,401
Oh, I got myself educated.
Just took longer than I thought.

754
00:40:00,161 --> 00:40:01,921
-But you kept going.
-Always.

755
00:40:02,001 --> 00:40:04,361
An education makes you unstoppable.

756
00:40:05,121 --> 00:40:07,121
Everything here is a fight for you.

757
00:40:07,201 --> 00:40:09,841
Don't you get tired?
What keeps you going?

758
00:40:11,121 --> 00:40:13,201
The promise of tomorrow.

759
00:40:13,281 --> 00:40:16,801
When today isn't working,
tomorrow is what you have.

760
00:40:18,121 --> 00:40:20,281
You married? Got a job back home?

761
00:40:20,361 --> 00:40:22,841
Not married and I'm a police officer.

762
00:40:23,721 --> 00:40:26,601
-You're police?
-Yup. Just starting.

763
00:40:26,681 --> 00:40:27,801
Not where I want to be.

764
00:40:27,921 --> 00:40:31,041
-Mmm. Where is it you want to be?
-In charge.

765
00:40:31,121 --> 00:40:32,721
(LAUGHS) Amen to that.

766
00:40:34,841 --> 00:40:36,481
Shouldn't you be finishing up?

767
00:40:36,601 --> 00:40:40,281
If a job is worth doing,
it is worth doing well.

768
00:40:40,681 --> 00:40:42,321
But don't you have a bus to get?

769
00:40:42,401 --> 00:40:44,121
I can always walk.

770
00:41:02,841 --> 00:41:06,041
Hey, Doc, I don't want to be an alarmist

771
00:41:06,121 --> 00:41:08,361
but this bus seems a bit emptier
than last night.

772
00:41:09,081 --> 00:41:10,561
(SIGHS)

773
00:41:11,041 --> 00:41:12,921
DOCTOR: No, that's bad.

774
00:41:13,041 --> 00:41:16,481
We need the bus to be full.
Come on, Ryan.

775
00:41:16,561 --> 00:41:20,521
Excuse me, excuse me. Old people.
The buses are still running.

776
00:41:20,601 --> 00:41:22,161
We're gonna walk.

777
00:41:22,241 --> 00:41:24,921
The buses are coming, I promise.
Please, just wait for the bus.

778
00:41:25,001 --> 00:41:27,001
You don't tell me what to do, boy.

779
00:41:28,681 --> 00:41:30,161
Oh, man. This place.

780
00:41:30,281 --> 00:41:33,161
Passengers down, white passengers down.
Not good.

781
00:41:40,041 --> 00:41:43,721
-I think that should just about...
-Love it.

782
00:41:44,681 --> 00:41:47,481
Let's go. I'll walk you out.
Pay you on the way.

783
00:41:55,481 --> 00:41:58,641
Ah, I might have known.
Pretty boy blocking the road.

784
00:41:58,721 --> 00:42:00,641
Right then. This is on me.

785
00:42:02,361 --> 00:42:05,401
Mate, move your car so the bus
gets through. Come on, out of the way.

786
00:42:05,481 --> 00:42:07,601
No, you get out of my way.

787
00:42:07,681 --> 00:42:10,921
Just give it up, will you?
Cut your losses.

788
00:42:11,001 --> 00:42:12,241
You're not gonna win tonight.

789
00:42:12,321 --> 00:42:15,321
I already have.
I know what should happen.

790
00:42:15,441 --> 00:42:16,721
And even if it gets past here,

791
00:42:16,801 --> 00:42:20,401
that bus is at least three passengers
short of what it should be by now.

792
00:42:20,481 --> 00:42:23,961
Parks won't be asked to stand,
she won't protest

793
00:42:24,041 --> 00:42:26,241
and your kind
won't get above themselves.

794
00:42:26,321 --> 00:42:29,881
-My "kind"?
-Yeah, your kind.

795
00:42:30,721 --> 00:42:32,001
Stay in your place.

796
00:42:32,721 --> 00:42:35,041
Mate, you're living in the past.

797
00:42:35,121 --> 00:42:37,401
In fact, you like the past that much,

798
00:42:37,481 --> 00:42:39,921
-so why don't you stay there?
-(BEEP)

799
00:42:41,601 --> 00:42:44,001
Oh! Oh, it worked.

800
00:42:44,121 --> 00:42:46,161
Nice one, Ryan. Thanks, Ryan.

801
00:42:46,801 --> 00:42:49,161
Move the car, clear the route,
find the bus,

802
00:42:49,241 --> 00:42:52,761
and Rosa Parks will change the world.
Good, here we go.

803
00:42:58,201 --> 00:43:00,281
DOCTOR: Yaz!
Yeah, yeah, yeah, how's it going?

804
00:43:00,361 --> 00:43:02,041
Mrs Parks fixed your coat.

805
00:43:02,121 --> 00:43:06,121
Oh, thank you, Mrs Parks.
Beautiful work. Much appreciated.

806
00:43:06,201 --> 00:43:07,881
You're welcome, ma'am.

807
00:43:11,601 --> 00:43:14,801
RYAN: Don't shut the door.
Don't drive off! One more coming on.

808
00:43:18,281 --> 00:43:22,081
(PANTING) Found you.
I just got rid of Krasko.

809
00:43:22,161 --> 00:43:24,441
-How??
-TI borrowed this.

810
00:43:24,521 --> 00:43:27,161
I think I dialled the settings
as far back as it can go.

811
00:43:27,281 --> 00:43:28,361
He's gone.

812
00:43:28,441 --> 00:43:30,401
Use the door for coloreds.

813
00:43:33,281 --> 00:43:35,001
Law's a law.

814
00:43:43,041 --> 00:43:44,561
DOCTOR: Let's move back.

815
00:43:57,441 --> 00:44:01,081
GRAHAM: Hey, Doc, Rosa's on board,
Blake's driving, we're good, right?

816
00:44:02,281 --> 00:44:04,121
YASMIN: What's the matter?
What are you doing?

817
00:44:04,201 --> 00:44:05,441
Counting seats.

818
00:44:06,801 --> 00:44:08,721
YASMIN: Has it worked?
Have we done enough?

819
00:44:08,801 --> 00:44:10,121
I don't know.

820
00:44:11,521 --> 00:44:12,961
We get off at the next stop, right?

821
00:44:15,321 --> 00:44:17,441
Empire Theatre, yeah.

822
00:44:20,441 --> 00:44:24,201
Right, come on then. We can go.
Job done. History is safe.

823
00:44:28,721 --> 00:44:30,641
-Well, come on then.
-Doctor?

824
00:44:30,721 --> 00:44:32,401
Don't get off, Graham.

825
00:44:33,201 --> 00:44:36,801
If we get off, there's enough
empty seats for white passengers.

826
00:44:36,881 --> 00:44:39,641
Rosa won't be asked to move.
We have to stay on.

827
00:44:39,721 --> 00:44:43,161
We were here. We're part of the story.

828
00:44:43,241 --> 00:44:44,841
Part of history.

829
00:44:44,921 --> 00:44:46,761
No, no. I don't want to be part of this.

830
00:44:46,841 --> 00:44:49,801
We have to. I'm sorry.
We have to not help her.

831
00:44:54,801 --> 00:44:56,761
I'm gonna need those seats back there.

832
00:45:02,641 --> 00:45:05,601
You all better make it light on
yourselves and let me have those seats.

833
00:45:49,801 --> 00:45:51,241
Stand up now.

834
00:45:52,441 --> 00:45:54,561
I don't think I should have to.

835
00:45:55,401 --> 00:45:57,721
(SHOUTING) Are you going to stand up?

836
00:46:01,401 --> 00:46:02,721
No.

837
00:46:04,521 --> 00:46:07,481
If you don't stand,
I'm gonna have you arrested.

838
00:46:11,241 --> 00:46:12,761
You may do that.

839
00:46:21,241 --> 00:46:24,801
# You're broken down and tired

840
00:46:24,881 --> 00:46:29,081
# Of living life on a merry-go-round

841
00:46:29,161 --> 00:46:33,001
# And you can't find the fighter

842
00:46:33,081 --> 00:46:36,481
# But I see it in you
So we gonna walk it out

843
00:46:36,561 --> 00:46:41,961
# And move mountains

844
00:46:43,601 --> 00:46:45,801
# And I'll rise up

845
00:46:45,881 --> 00:46:47,801
# I'll rise like the day

846
00:46:47,881 --> 00:46:49,761
# I'll rise up

847
00:46:49,841 --> 00:46:51,961
# I'll rise unafraid

848
00:46:52,041 --> 00:46:54,081
# I'll rise up

849
00:46:54,161 --> 00:46:58,161
# And I'll do it a thousand times again

850
00:46:59,641 --> 00:47:02,161
# And I'll rise up

851
00:47:02,241 --> 00:47:04,121
# High like the waves

852
00:47:04,201 --> 00:47:06,041
# I'll rise up

853
00:47:06,121 --> 00:47:08,241
# In spite of the ache

854
00:47:08,321 --> 00:47:10,321
# I'll rise up

855
00:47:10,441 --> 00:47:14,881
# And I'll do it a thousand times again

856
00:47:16,201 --> 00:47:20,321
# For you, oh, oh, oh

857
00:47:20,401 --> 00:47:24,681
# For you, oh, oh, oh

858
00:47:24,761 --> 00:47:27,321
# For you

859
00:47:28,561 --> 00:47:32,241
# For you #

860
00:47:33,801 --> 00:47:36,081
DOCTOR: On Monday, the boycotts begin.

861
00:47:36,161 --> 00:47:38,921
Across Montgomery
people refuse to use the buses

862
00:47:39,001 --> 00:47:41,001
as a response to Rosa's arrest.

863
00:47:42,001 --> 00:47:46,561
And in just over a year,
on the 21st of December, 1956,

864
00:47:46,641 --> 00:47:49,721
segregation on buses in Montgomery
was ended.

865
00:47:50,161 --> 00:47:51,481
So it all worked out for her.

866
00:47:51,561 --> 00:47:53,521
No, life's still hard for Rosa.

867
00:47:54,281 --> 00:47:56,361
She loses her job, so does her husband.

868
00:47:56,441 --> 00:47:59,721
It's a struggle. They keep fighting.

869
00:48:00,721 --> 00:48:03,521
And in June 1999,

870
00:48:03,641 --> 00:48:07,201
Rosa receives the Congressional Medal
from President Clinton.

871
00:48:07,281 --> 00:48:09,681
The highest award given to any civilian,

872
00:48:09,761 --> 00:48:13,761
recognising her as a living icon
for freedom.

873
00:48:14,321 --> 00:48:17,401
It took so long, though. Her whole life.

874
00:48:17,481 --> 00:48:18,881
Yes, it did.

875
00:48:20,561 --> 00:48:22,481
But she changed the world.

876
00:48:23,561 --> 00:48:26,801
In fact, she changed the universe.

877
00:48:27,521 --> 00:48:28,841
Look at this.

878
00:48:35,521 --> 00:48:38,161
Asteroid 284996.

879
00:48:38,841 --> 00:48:40,881
Also known as Rosaparks.

880
00:48:55,521 --> 00:48:56,681
# And we'll rise up

881
00:48:56,761 --> 00:48:58,761
# Rise like the waves

882
00:48:58,841 --> 00:49:00,841
# We'll rise up

883
00:49:00,921 --> 00:49:02,961
# In spite of the ache

884
00:49:03,041 --> 00:49:05,081
# We'll rise up

885
00:49:05,161 --> 00:49:09,761
# And we'll do it
A thousand times again

886
00:49:10,921 --> 00:49:14,961
# For you, oh, oh, oh, oh, oh

887
00:49:15,041 --> 00:49:19,001
# For you, oh, oh, oh, oh, oh

888
00:49:19,601 --> 00:49:22,961
# For you, oh, oh, oh, oh, oh

889
00:49:23,041 --> 00:49:25,281
# For you #

890
00:49:27,161 --> 00:49:28,321
We're home!

891
00:49:28,401 --> 00:49:30,281
Who are you?
How do you know my daughter?

892
00:49:31,041 --> 00:49:33,641
WOMAN: Something's happening
with the spiders in this city.

893
00:49:33,761 --> 00:49:35,201
Argh! Argh!

